District 8 4-H & Youth Development
August 7 at 9:50 AM ¬∑

We finish out this week with Catarina Salazar-Canales, from Bell County 4-H. Cat had this to say:

This is my 8th and final year in 4-H. My favorite thing to do in 4-H is compete in food challenge. One super boring thing about me is that I like having a plan and planning events. This year I am most looking forward to meeting and reaching youth from across the district. One thing I want the district 8 members to know about me is that I enjoy competing in contests as well as serving as a leader.

#4Hgrowstrueleaders

State Fair of Texas Livestock Exhibitors
July 17 at 10:17 AM ¬∑

Happy Friday, folks!

Today we are very excited to announce phase one of our revised schedule of events related to livestock market shows for 2020!

Barring any orders are in place by local, state, or federal agencies regarding health and safety concerns related to COVID-19, the State Fair of Texas plans to move forward with the following schedule to support Texas youth, while implementing all preventive measures recommended by the CDC and other relevant health agencies. Please check out this page for the schedule of events - https://bigtex.com/livestock

Any changes or additional information regarding the revised 2020 livestock show, including further details on non-market youth livestock events, will be coming by the end of July.

Balance is an essential characteristic when evaluating livestock at a judging contest. A balanced sheep will have plenty of muscle while maintaining the appropriate degree of finish. The lamb should be long and clean about his neck which should connect smoothly to the top of the shoulder. A smooth level top line and hip design will add to the balance of a wether as well. #texas4h #youthlivestockmatters #livestockjudging #livestockjudging #tipthursday

District 8 4-H & Youth Development
April 21 at 3:25 PM ¬∑

Join in the fun! Here is your change to contribute to one of our district activities!

Questions & Answers for Consumer Quiz ‚Äì deadline to submit is April 27th

D8 youth (grades 3-12) have the opportunity to provide questions and answers for the above quiz. This is just another way of strengthening knowledge of various consumer products. So study your guide, available at http://texas4-h.tamu.edu/wp-content/uploads/consumer_decision_making_categories_descriptions_2020.pdf, and start compiling questions and answers. In case you need some help, here‚Äôs an example:

Category: Activewear

Question: Choose activewear that fits your ___ and your ___.

Answers: A. time, energy B. body, workout C. style, curves D. space, closet

Correct Answer: B. body, workout

When you have your questions and answers ready, add them to the google form at http://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLScf6UqL4eBvs9F4Lu28zjsCRJsEOlKP1N245j3z99phPaLO9w/viewform. There will be a drawing for prizes for those who submit questions and answers ‚Äì the more you submit, the more chances you‚Äôll have.

Now is the time.....Time to try something new! Over the next few weeks, we will be hosting several opportunities for our 4-H members to expand their project learning through virtual educational events. Monday begins the CDM project event, with the question collection part of our opportunity. This event will allow to have both a leadership experience and a learning experience at the district level.

Virtual Challenge
In an effort to provide as much of a Consumer Decision Making contest experience, we are hosting this Virtual Challenge in which you will judge classes of consumer products.

Challenge will be open April 20th ‚Äì April 27th

Consumer Quiz
The quiz will have participants answering questions related to the consumer products outlined in the current Texas 4-H Categories and Descriptions guide. Quiz will be open May 4th ‚Äì May 8th. We will release the quiz link by May 4th.

(Check with your County Ext. Agents for the links and game codes).

We will be handing out some super cool 4-H Swag to those top winners of our game!

post_text:
Bell County 4-H Round Up - CANCELED

Good afternoon everyone. Due to COVID-19 restrictions set in place in the county, we will not be having the 4-H Round Up and Share the Fun contests that was scheduled for Monday, March 30th. The entry deadline of Friday, March 27th has not changed! You must sumbit entry forms to Sheryl.Long@ag.tamu.edu by Friday, March 27th.

If no 2 youth members are entered in the same age division and category, the single entry will automatically advance to the District 8 contest. If there are 2 or more youth members entered in the same age division and category, we will have a virtual contest to determine the winner. You will be notified on wether or not a virutal contest is needed. Spread the word and stay sanitized!

Today's activity comes from the Foods & Nutrition project.

Recipe creation is an important tool to have in your foods arsenal. Today, we challenge you to find 3-5 ingredients in your house and create a new recipe (something you may have not ever made or tried before). This does not have to be anything that anyone has heard of. We want to see your creativity come out! Create your recipe, make your dish, taste it, and share that recipe with us! You can drop a picture in the comments. We can't wait to see what you cook up!

post_text:
The livestock judging team had a busy weekend!

A BIG congratulations to Kaylee Eaton on winning two contests in a row!! She was the Junior High Point Individual at the East Central and San Antonio Livestock Judging contests back to back days.

Jackson Bragg was 20th HPI at the East Central contest.

The Junior team of Kaylee Eaton, Jackson Bragg, Macy Morris, and Madeline Rakowitz were 6th Overall in San Antonio today.

It was a good day for all 21 Bell County 4-H Livestock Judging team members who work together, push each other, and get better all the time!!

Great job to all of our contestants that completed yesterday! Big thanks and congratulations to our coach Michael Canales!

March 5, 2019 at 11:55 AM ¬∑

There are many different areas to evaluate muscle in sheep and goats! This makes it challenging for some people to evaluate! Just keep in mind a naturally big-hipped, wide-made lamb or goat will have the ability to lay more muscle and mass onto their skeleton, where as a narrow-based animal doesn‚Äôt have the frame to carry as
much muscle. #livestockjudging #tipstuesday

shared_text:
Texas Youth Livestock and Agriculture
January 23, 2019 at 12:55 PM ¬∑

Howdy! Meet Clara Steglich, a Livestock Ambassador from Holland, Texas. Clara plans to attend Texas A&M University in the fall, where she hopes to become an agricultural science teacher. Clara said the most influential experience as an ambassador was the Argentina Agricultural Experience, ‚ÄúI could have never imagined getting to see all of the amazing sites and experiencing all of the incredible learning opportunities that I was fortunate enough to participate in. Being able to compare the United States to Argentina and view all of the differences was an experience in itself.‚Äù As an ambassador, Clara has been able to share her Ag story with the public at stock shows, grocery stores, and on social media. Clara credits her personal growth to the ambassador program, calling it career-shaping. We are proud of the work Clara as done! #ambassadorspotlight #agriculture

post_text:
The Bell County Youth Fair Scholarship application is now available! Submission deadline is April 5th.

To be eligible, you must:
1. Be a high school senior for 2018-2019.
2. Be a participant of the 2019 Bell County Youth Fair and Livestock Show, plus have participated in the fair a minimum of one other year.
3. Be eligible to attend a two-or four-year College, university or technical school as a full-time student (12 hours per semester) for the 2019-2020 school year.
4. Complete this scholarship application form and submit it to the Bell County Extension Office, Attn: BCYF Scholarship Program, 1605 North Main, Room 102, Belton, TX 76513 by 5:00 p.m. on April 5, 2019. Any applications received after 5:00 p.m. April 5, 2019 will not be considered.

Application can be found on https://agrilife.org/bell4h/4-h-activities/scholarships/ or on the Bell County Youth Fair website.

post_text: Here's a few pictures that we'd like to share from our Bell-Milam Youth Agribusiness tour! Josh Rodriguez at Capital Farm Credit, David and Sandra Waiser at Milam County Jr. Livestock Association, Jennifer Ramthun at Purina, and April Walker at Datamars- you have helped us make a huge impact on a great group of youth!

Are your children interested in the livestock industry? Enroll them in our youth program! Our program gives them the opportunity to participate in a live cattle evaluation, beef quality demonstration, and a beef fabrication hands-on demonstration. Our program is only open to the first 45 participants that sign up. Registration fees for youth are $100 if signed up before July 30th.
